President Uhuru Kenyatta has appointed Brigadier Vincent Loonena as the pioneer Director General of the Kenya Coast Guard Service. Loonena, who has a past career spanning 20 years with the Kenya Defence Forces, was managing director Defence Forces Medical Insurance Scheme. He served in the position for four months. The Kenya Coast Guard Service will officially be launched by the Head of State on Monday, November 19, at Liwatoni in Mombasa. The service was established by The Coast Guard Act, 2018, and was operationalised on October 22 when Interior Cabinet Secretary Fred Matiang’i published the legislation in the Kenya Gazette. The agency will be responsible for protecting the country’s waters against dumping of harmful wastes and pollutants, search and rescue services, and the arrest of illegal fishermen. Read; Uhuru signs into law new taxes passed by MPs More on this; Cabinet proposes creation of Coast Guard Service Click here for the latest political news